result.execSummary:
The defendant Joseph M. Mullins was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse - Infliction of Physical Pain or Injury, Repeater], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).
  • Bail Jumping-Misdemeanor [Modifiers: Repeater], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Transcript of 2/12/2016 Sentencing Hearing on Revocation

Court's Response to Defendant's Motion for Postconviction Relief - Mr. Mullins: I am forwarding this to your trial attorney, Karl Huebner, as it is his responsibility to file a Notice of Postconviction Relief if you request him to do so. He can also contact the public defender about appointment of postconviction counsel. Please note the 20 day time period ended on 3-3-16. This Motion was not filed until 3-7-16 RRK

[MK] cases #13CF128, #13CF184, #15CM370 called at 1:43pm. 
Defendant Joseph M. Mullins in court, in custody, with Attorney Karl E Huebner.  ADA Theresa Beck appears for the State of Wisconsin.  
ADA Beck verifies victim rights compliance. 
Sentencing arguments are given by ADA Beck, by Attorney Huebner.


In Case #13CF184 on Count #5, the Court sentences Mr. Mullins to 4 years, with an Initial Term of Confinement in Prison of 30 months, and the maximum time to serve on Extended Supervision of 18 months.  This sentence is consecutive to any previously imposed sentences.
The Court finds that Mr. Mullins is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program "Boot Camp".
The Court finds that Mr. Mullins is not eligible for the Substance Abuse Program.
The Court gives  0 days credit for time already served. However the Court indicates that it will consider a stipulation when the attorneys submit this; if such a stipulation cannot be reached, counsel may request a hearing.
The Court orders as conditions of Extended Supervision:
--to pay costs 


In Case #13CF128 on Counts #2, #3, and #4 each, the Court sentences Mr. Mullins to 2 years, with an Initial Term of Confinement in Prison of 18 months, and the maximum time to serve on Extended Supervision of 6 months. The sentence in Count #2 is consecutive to the sentence in Case #13CF184.  The sentences in Counts #3 and #4 are concurrent with each other and with Count #2. 
The Court finds that Mr. Mullins is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program "Boot Camp".
The Court finds that Mr. Mullins is not eligible for the Substance Abuse Program.
The Court gives  0 days credit for time already served.  However the Court indicates that it will consider a stipulation when the attorneys submit this; if such a stipulation cannot be reached, counsel may request a hearing.
The Court orders as conditions of Extended Supervision:
--to pay costs 

In Case #15CM370, on Counts #2 and #5 each, the Court sentences Mr. Mullins to 90 days in Jail concurrent
--0 days credit for time already served given
--pay costs including the DNA surcharge and Domestic surcharge on each count; the Court orders civil judgment on the amounts due in this case, and the Court indicates that the Department of Corrections is allowed to collect the victim/witness surcharge or other charges on those counts as mandated by state law 


Felony Firearm and Voting-rights prohibitions/warnings given
Explanation of Determinate Sentence form given to the Defendant
recess 2:14 pm, reconvene 2:14pm. 
Attorney Misal Diaz-Martinez, who is present in the courtroom gallery, voices a request that the Court order that Mr. Mullins is to remain in the Jefferson County Jail so that he is available at that location to assist Attorney Diaz-Martinez in preparation for trial on separate cases that is schedule for 4/4/16 and 4/5/16 in Branch II. 
The Court indicates that it is not aware of any legal authority for this.
recess 2:16pm.

Case called at 10:05am [mo]
Defendant Joseph M. Mullins in court, in custody with Attorney Karl Huebner.   DA Susan Happ appears for the State of Wisconsin.

The Court addresses Atty. Huebner's request for Mr. Mullins other cases to have the Sentencing After Revocation hearing today.

With no objection from Counsel, The Court delays the sentencing in this case to allow the Revocation Order and Warrant from DOC to be received.

The Court and Counsel discuss scheduling.
The Court directs the Clerk to note that Cases 13CF128 and 13CF184 should be scheduled for Sentencing after Revocation at the time of the Sentencing in 15CF274.
